As a JSON file parser, there are a few common structural errors that one might encounter when parsing a JSON file. Here are some potential difficulties and obstacles that might hinder the process of identifying these errors:

1. Missing or extra commas: JSON objects and arrays use commas to separate elements. A missing or extra comma can lead to a parsing error.

2. Incorrect quotes: JSON requires double quotes for strings and object keys. Single quotes, unquoted keys, or missing quotes can cause errors.

3. Curly braces and square brackets: Every opening brace '{' or bracket '[' needs a corresponding closing brace '}' or bracket ']'. Mismatched or missing brackets/braces will result in an error.

4. Data type issues: JSON has specific data types (string, number, object, array, boolean, null). Assigning the wrong data type to a value could cause an issue.

5. Trailing commas: While some parsers might be lenient, a trailing comma after the last element in an object or array is technically incorrect in JSON.

6. Encoding problems: JSON files should be UTF-8 encoded. If the file has a different encoding, special characters may not be parsed correctly.

7. Comments: Standard JSON does not support comments, so any comments in the file would cause a parsing error.

8. Nested structures depth: Deeply nested structures can sometimes be problematic for parsers with limited stack depth or memory.

Identifying structural errors in JSON requires careful examination of the syntax and structure. I will be able to provide a more accurate assessment once I see the actual JSON input file.
